Enterprise Application Architecture
Enterprise application architecture is the structured design of large-scale business applications used by organizations or enterprises.
It defines how an application should be built, how modules should connect, how data should flow, and how security, scalability, and maintenance should be handled.
Definition:-
Enterprise-level applications are large software systems such as:
Banking systems
E-commerce platforms
Hospital management systems
ERP systems
CRM applications
These applications must be reliable, secure, and scalable, so proper architecture is very important.
Main Layers of Enterprise Application Architecture
1. Presentation Layer (UI Layer)
This is the part users can see and interact with.
Examples:
Web pages
Mobile app screens
Dashboards
Example:
Login page
User profile page

2. Business Logic Layer (Application Layer)
This layer contains the main business rules and logic.
Examples:
Salary calculation
Order processing
Leave approval logic
Example:
“If employee leave is more than 10 days, manager approval is required.”

3. Data Access Layer
This layer communicates with the database.
Examples:
Insert data
Update records
Fetch reports
Example:
MySQL/PostgreSQL queries

4. Database Layer
This is where actual data is stored.
Examples:
Customer details
Employee records
Product information

Important Characteristics
Scalability
The application should handle more users without becoming slow.

Security
Data must be protected.
Examples:
Authentication
Authorization
Encryption

Maintainability
Future changes and updates should be easy to implement.

Availability
The application should remain online and accessible most of the time.

Common Architecture Types
Monolithic Architecture
Everything is built into a single application.
It is simple but difficult to manage at large scale.

Microservices Architecture
The application is divided into small independent services.
Examples:
Payment service
User service
Notification service
Large companies often use this approach.

Service-Oriented Architecture (SOA)
Different systems communicate through services.


